ey, leading me to argue in Intel Honesty ( https://stratechery.com/2024/int=
el-honesty/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBh=
c3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC=
5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJod=
HRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2ludGVsLWhvbmVzdHkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MzU4=
MTk1NTIsImlhdCI6MTczMzIyNzU1MiwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5=
lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZW=
dvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwid=
XNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.S532OcPX1T0VZ67FqAc8vqdB7yFlPkvW50xBxo0ssJn9AY2RlDyd2BvN=
7DbctPG0QlxeyC7aDOYxOZCqeWn5KtxYnqjWJQja0y3mvIonlcgUp9y8HCWk5FSlEVOdNYkj8UA=
lUlHRM5z5B-87qh_eOWKQblC3z725mq2C1-joeeCeTBkL3_tnW_dzAnxjTk6QvcJM7TlWbpwg19=
2n5gECleH7B-R3V6tSArToS5KrO40Fl0qAVFp2gQByZUH6JxK9oWTy-KHr84Eh6NmU5SqmWnfZP=
nrh-TVHOa4fbiQqM4VnOw1_iefGGne1D8AULkkELYInrGWbM4H_v1bFsdU8_A ) that my ini=
tial prescription was correct: Intel needed to split, because if the U.S. g=
overnment was going to spend the money necessary to make foundry competitiv=
e, it needed to be independent from Intel.

Then, last week, Intel finally got its CHIPS grant =E2=80=94 which to be cl=
ear, was necessary but not sufficient in terms of Intel=E2=80=99s cash need=
s =E2=80=94 with some significant strings attached. From Reuters ( https://=
www.reuters.com/technology/intels-786-billion-subsidy-deal-restricts-sale-i=
ts-manufacturing-unit-2024-11-28/ ) :

Intel said on Wednesday its deal for $7.86 billion in U.S. government subsi=
dies restricts the company=E2=80=99s ability to sell stakes in its chipmaki=
ng unit if it becomes an independent entity.

The U.S. Commerce Department announced the subsidy to Intel on Tuesday, par=
t of $39 billion for the sector including Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturin=
g Co and others in an effort to revitalize chip manufacturing in the United=
 States. Intel Chief Executive Pat Gelsinger in September said that the com=
pany planned to spin its chip manufacturing operations into a subsidiary, o=
pens new tab and was open to taking on outside investors in the unit, calle=
d Intel Foundry.

In a securities filing, Intel said on Wednesday the subsidies require it to=
 own at least 50.1% of Intel Foundry if the unit is separated into a new pr=
ivately held legal entity. If Intel Foundry becomes a public company and In=
tel itself is not the largest shareholder, the company could sell only 35% =
of Intel Foundry to any single shareholder before running into change-in-co=
ntrol provisions.

According to Intel=E2=80=99s filing ( https://www.intc.com/filings-reports/=
all-sec-filings/content/0000050863-24-000169/0000050863-24-000169.pdf ) , t=
he penalty for violating these provisions is a clawback of the money (altho=
ugh there is a broad provision for the Department of Commerce to =E2=80=9Ct=
ake other actions available=E2=80=9D). In other words, Intel could still ch=
ange its mind about a split, but it would have to do so now.

Thus we arrive at my best guess: the Intel board has cold feet about Intel=
=E2=80=99s foundry efforts, and this provision forced their hand. Note this=
 bit from the board statement ( https://www.intc.com/news-events/press-rele=
ases/detail/1719/intel-announces-retirement-of-ceo-pat-gelsinger ) about Ge=
lsinger=E2=80=99s exit:

Yeary continued, =E2=80=9CWhile we have made significant progress in regain=
ing manufacturing competitiveness and building the capabilities to be a wor=
ld-class foundry, we know that we have much more work to do at the company =
and are committed to restoring investor confidence. As a board, we know fir=
st and foremost that we must put our product group at the center of all we =
do. Our customers demand this from us, and we will deliver for them. With M=
J=E2=80=99s permanent elevation to CEO of Intel Products along with her int=
erim co-CEO role of Intel, we are ensuring the product group will have the =
resources needed to deliver for our customers. Ultimately, returning to pro=
cess leadership is central to product leadership, and we will remain focuse=
d on that mission while driving greater efficiency and improved profitabili=
ty.=E2=80=9D

The best way to =E2=80=9Cput our product group at the center of all we do=
=E2=80=9D is to preserve the ability to separate it from the foundry busine=
ss and potentially go fabless, just as AMD did 15 years ago. That option, h=
owever, is about to be foreclosed. Gelsinger, meanwhile, was clear with me =
that if the board wanted to potentially split the company, he was the wrong=
 CEO.

And now he=E2=80=99s retired, with an announcement retroactive to Sunday.

Ten Years Too Late
------------------

The Yeary in that excerpt is Frank Yeary; here is his board profile ( https=
://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/newsroom/biographies/biography-frank-d-y=
eary.html#gs.id1r45 ) :

Frank D. Yeary joined Intel Corporation=E2=80=99s board of directors in Mar=
ch 2009 and was named chair of the board in January 2023. Yeary is an indep=
endent director and is interim executive chair of the board.

He is managing member at Darwin Capital Advisors LLC, a private investment =
firm, and was executive chairman of CamberView Partners LLC, a corporate ad=
visory firm, until 2018. Prior to this time, Yeary was vice chancellor of t=
he University of California, Berkeley, and before that he spent 25 years in=
 the finance industry, including as global head of Mergers and Acquisitions=
 and as a member of the Management Committee at Citigroup Investment Bankin=
g.

I hesitate to pick on one person, given that the entire Intel board seems w=
holly unsuited to the job ( https://stratechery.com/2024/intel-concerns-fub=
o-blocks-venu/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5L=
nBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9=
ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6Wy=
JodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2ludGVsLWNvbmNlcm5zLWZ1Ym8tYmxvY2tzL=
XZlbnUvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MzU4MTk1NTIsImlhdCI6MTczMzIyNzU1MiwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6=
Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTp=
yZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJzdWIiOiJSc2V1WU=
U4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.Ikl5Mfn8xmHmaUnlVJwyIa2o-gm4g=
SnnRYjkDs7q6r7TV-BiBw6Z7_ZvZYrlHzVsju-eAR2pa-wSrYka_-tw7wy-1OGvR9ufn9LzqN6h=
PomviQFS9OHuZGOdd121La3a8XYCDimfzqoN0B5lrBpK6A_oj45YCXi4RgCfxK8Mv2GN9ui4EAp=
zOhXJGFAbdlHyNdAXTeJYliCHLSFlpTWYmmAtj6wXXASfLjbxBpPrKqdIfBDrjppWqqHxtu8N1V=
SXBGedO5YMlz_1-xxi3VA9fVbFWxHsS_JqoaTVCo0n_8Qxth21GpXuMjklWeBI5aey0noY9PFL7=
JavEGcSWqKt_g ) , but it is pretty striking how Yeary=E2=80=99s tenure perf=
ectly matches Intel=E2=80=99s disaster era, the hallmark of which was the p=
rioritization of financial returns over building for the future. Intel fail=
ed to become a foundry when it should have, failed to develop GPU-based com=
puting capabilities, and lost its manufacturing leadership, even as its sto=
ck price surged with those server chip orders and, early in Gelsinger=E2=80=
=99s tenure, COVID-driven consumer PC sales.

That surge also obscured the need for necessary moves on Gelsinger=E2=80=99=
s part, including slashing the dividend and reducing the size of Intel=E2=
=80=99s workforce, even though his IDM 2.0 initiative would need massive am=
ounts of cash. In truth, though =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this was the realization=
 I came to a few months ago =E2=80=94=C2=A0I=E2=80=99m not sure that Gelsin=
ger ever had a chance. Everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0including me and the U.S. go=
vernment =E2=80=94 wanted him to succeed, but (1) there just isn=E2=80=99t =
an economic rationale for a TSMC alternative absent geopolitics and (2) Int=
el is particularly unsuited to becoming a foundry given its internally-focu=
sed culture and, relatedly, the widespread antipathy and lack of trust amon=
gst the companies it needed to secure as customers (all of which, I would n=
ote, is sure to be exacerbated by a charge to put Intel=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
product group at the center of all we do=E2=80=9D).

It is a truism that it is not enough to be right, because you need to get t=
he timing correct as well, and I think that applies to Gelsinger=E2=80=99s =
IDM 2.0 initiative. His plan is what Intel should have done as soon as they=
 missed mobile: the next best alternative to selling your own mobile chips =
would have been to make them for others, and that in turn would have positi=
oned Intel to make chips for AI as well. Yeary and company, however, chased=
 shareholder returns, which arguably left them with only one depressing cho=
ice: do whatever is necessary to preserve the fading x86 franchise, Gelsing=
er=E2=80=99s valiant foundry efforts and U.S. national security concerns be=
 damned.

I am, to be fair, reading a lot into this news; perhaps there were other fa=
ctors that went into this sudden decision, and Intel will continue down the=
 path Gelsinger started on. I think it=E2=80=99s much more likely, though, =
that are witnessing the final chapter of the company that defined Silicon V=
alley. Intel will move more and more of its chips to TSMC, who I=E2=80=99m =
sure will offer them a generous deal in exchange for no longer being a pote=
ntial competitor, while the U.S. government will have to face the reality t=
hat its national security needs will require more than the desperation and =
resolve of a patriotic prodigal son trying to do the right thing ten years =
too late.

